        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer267993498" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4139674217189377046">The 2nd edition. Concentrated knowledge; yet NOT written in impenetrable ‘academicalese.’ McGee&apos;s ability to amass, sort, analyse, and order an enormous amount of relevant information is awesomely impressive. He makes the average PhD. thesis look sheepish.<br/><br/>This is definitely a reference book to be laid open on a table and lovingly dipped into by an enquiring mind. Not held open in the hands: too heavy. However, I’ll keep my (much smaller) copy of the 1st edition, because I want to follow how McGe</span>
  <span id="freeText4139674217189377046" style="display:none">The 2nd edition. Concentrated knowledge; yet NOT written in impenetrable ‘academicalese.’ McGee's ability to amass, sort, analyse, and order an enormous amount of relevant information is awesomely impressive. He makes the average PhD. thesis look sheepish.<br /><br />This is definitely a reference book to be laid open on a table and lovingly dipped into by an enquiring mind. Not held open in the hands: too heavy. However, I’ll keep my (much smaller) copy of the 1st edition, because I want to follow how McGee’s thinking has modified and changed over the twenty years between 1984 and 2004.<br /><br />Every school library ought to have a copy on their shelves. How better to turn children onto the joys of science than a book on ‘edible science’?<br /></span>
